Last night I dreamt the whole night long
I woke with a head full of songs
I spent the whole day
I wrote 'em down, but its a shame
Tonight I'll burn the lyrics,
'Cause every chorus was your name

Break this tired old routine
And this time don't make me leave

It's been a long day without you, my friend And I'll tell you all about it when I see you again We've come a long way from where we began Oh, I'll tell you all about it when I see you again Lilith doesn't like it at first, and tells him so. "She'll live another fifty years, maybe a century if she's lucky," the queen of Hell says to the emperor of the North, pale lashes dipped in thought. Cale shrugs, a nearly imperceptible lift of his shoulders. "Your children approve of my choice. Should you not concede defeat?" "My children, yes," Lilith huffs, dismissive - "they are fond of fragile amusements. Anna will die, Cale, as we all must. All of us except you and the other gods. Marry one of your own kind, for your own heart's sake." Cale takes Lilith's jaw in hand, turning her head to the side to inspect a yellowing bruise behind her ear. Lilith jerks out of his hold, mouth set in an unreadable line. "I will marry a god if you divorce an angel," the emperor says calmly. The queen looks away, chin lifted and eyes blank. * The wedding is a lavish affair, and (incomplete)

Howl looks at his father sometimes and experiences a strange disconnect. No, he thinks, I cannot possibly be this creature's son. For Rociel is perfection incarnate, slim like a woman but sharp like a man, neither angel, demon, nor those walking meat-sacks known as human. Rociel never gets sick, hardly sleeps, eats as a matter of formality - someone, somewhere told Serafuite that sentient two-leggers sit down and put organic matter in their mouths, so Rociel accepted this novelty and joined in the pantomime of external sustenance. Howl suspects it was his mother who insisted upon the concept of family meals, probably lonely for the bustling dining hall of Pandaemonium, and his father rarely denies her anything. The secret to a happy marriage, Ahri joked once, and their mother smiled. Howl looks at his parents together and wonders what first drew them to each other, and then what kept them from drifting apart; certainly they are two tectonic plates that must someday break off in opposite directions after shifting against one another for a hundred years. Someday, something will set off the fault lines and the crust will break open like an egg, spilling forth all the discontent that two people cannot help but build up between themselves. Howl can often see himself in his mother, tangible evidence linking progenitor and progeny, and it is a queer sort of comfort to be even a small part of something that carries such tremendous weight. He is not strong, or tall or clever, but he is the product of someone strong and tall and clever, and therefore his existence must reflect some worth. They have the same short temper and easy mirth, the same fascination with the natural world. Rociel is not a product of the natural world, and it shows - his ethereal appearance can hush a raucous crowd or silence a lone dissenter whether or not he utters a single word, and poor soldier-nurse Katan was swept up by this affront to all gods and nature a very long time ago. Howl pities Katan from the bottom of his shallow heart, wishes there were someone who could divert the angel's obsessive affections away from a being so far removed from his level as to be in another universe altogether. Lilith complements Rociel so well because she can love him without losing herself, a nigh impossible feat for anyone with a constitution less mighty than that of the devil queen. Not that Katan isn't powerful, and Howl has sometimes worried that things might come to blows between his sometime-guardian and his mother, but there is something fundamental lacking in Katan's soul, an absence that lets himself be lead along like a one-eyed dog. His mother could survive without his father, Howl is certain, but Katan would surely perish without the generous hand that scatters crumbs before him. Howl is too afraid to ask either of his parents why they are together, and he is pathetically grateful for the quaint notion of family meals and other times when it is just the three of them, content in each other's presence and unmindful of prior commitments to kin and kingdom. He is even happy that unlike either of his parents, he can fall ill with common ailments - whenever he develops an infection in his weak bronchial tubes, his mother brings him tea and presents, and his father sits and reads to him until he falls asleep. Both sovereigns find some way to bring their work into the sickroom, and Howl drifts through his recovery in a fog of codeine and utter peace, bracketed by the two most powerful people in Heaven. Lee finds him an old picture book full of human tales, knights slaying dragons and maidens weeping in towers, and Howl begins carrying it around everywhere, even to school. He studies the pictures very carefully, impressed with the image of flaxen-haired princes sallying forth to battle evil in various guises. He thinks of all the princes he knows, and none seem to fit this image. I am a sort of prince, Howl thinks to himself in the middle of grammar lessons, absently stroking the inked face of Arthur of Camelot. The demons refer to him this way, a standard title for any of Lilith's male descendants, but the angels don't quite see Rociel as a king - more so an immutable fixture, the incontrovertible victor in a brief, bizarre test of succession. Neither God nor Adam, he is simply Serafuite, and perfect. If I am a prince, then I can be like the heroes in my picture book, Howl thinks. Then I could be worthy of my father. He tests this image in his mind and finds it pleasing. Lee is like the king of Antenora, thinks Howl. And I will be his charming prince. The composition professor raps on her desk with a pencil, calling all wool-gatherers back to the lesson at present. The boy seated to Howl's left throws him a conspiratorial grin, and Howl smiles back, serene. Howl looks at his father that night, across the table during another family meal, while his mother is discussing Roman tactical maneuvers with Lord Bee and General Sofie - Rociel is poking interestedly at a flan, apparently amused by its jiggling constitution, head tilted towards Lilith as if half-listening to the history lesson. Howl imagines himself and his father as brave knights rushing to his mother's aid, slaying fire-breathing dragons and hydras and all manner of fantastical beasties whose heads already adorn his mother's trophy room in reality. Riding in on their glossy steeds, they would flash their silver swords and rescue peasant villages and fair damsels all the day long, returning home to their castle amidst a parade of grateful citizens. The pictures in his head make him smile, then laugh outright with pleasure - General Sofie cuts off his explanation, and Lilith reaches over to tweak Howl's ear. "No daydreams at the table, my precious half-wit." Howl protests the gentle insult, but Lord Bee is smiling so he knows it's only in jest. His father nudges him under the table, and they share a glance of understanding. Go on dreaming, Serafuite's eyes seem to say, crescent-shaped with mirth. I am a charming prince, Howl tells himself, a promise.

(I'm holy I want you to know it) You're all I need to survive (I'm holy I want you to know it) Blind devotion (I'm holy I want you to know it) And you'll be my sacrifice (I'm holy I want you to know it) You say you love... I worship, high praises My longing drives me crazy for you My kingdom for your graces I'm not gonna tell nobody I'm not gonna tell nobody bout you Lilith wakes up in the dead of night, pupils dilated and heart-rate accelerated to a level that would kill a lesser demon, her vision blurred and her lungs constricted, unable to utter a single sound as purple lightning spears the black sky beyond the window. She draws in a ragged breath, strips off her sweat-soaked nightgown and sits naked in bed for a minute, forcing her heart to calm its frantic, rabbiting pace. Once she can think with a clear head again, she pulls the sheets around herself like a cloak and tries to follow the thread of memory that will lead back to the origin of a nightmare so jarring as to wake her with pure, unfiltered fear. The baku usually consume her dreams like sugar floss, spooling anxieties through their jaws and swallowing every last needless doubt. She wants her husband. It's strange that he hasn't appeared yet, as in the rare instances when something jolted her from sleep and summoned Rociel like a warning bell. He never leaves her to her suffering. It is hard for her to fear anything in Serafita's presence. She tries to call him, but no sound emerges. It feels as though the inner walls of her chest are coated in a thick layer of dust. "Damn it," Lilith finally coughs, enraged at the audacity. Her suspicions are confirmed by the solid shadows that split off from the darkness and move towards her like a lava flow, surging up onto the bed and curling around her legs. She smacks her left hand onto the nearest dark blob, the diamonds from her wedding band setting off white sparks that are accompanied by a noise of annoyance from the source of the shadow. "Get out of here," the white queen hisses, attempting to pry the inky grip from her ankles. The shadows ripple in response, then subside to form a tall figure garbed in black. Sharp teeth flash in a grin, pale features seeming to glow with eerie moonlight. "It's so hard to contact you these days," says the devil king. "Lucifer, I swear -" "Don't insult us both with idle threats, my flower. I know that you are... displeased with my actions recently, but your efforts to keep me away are half-hearted at best." Lilith rests her chin on her knees, keeping the sheets wrapped tight around herself and trying to summon up enough anger to forcibly expel Lucifer from her bedroom. Rociel taught her how to set the wards, powerful old things rarely deployed now that Etanenmenki faced no significant threat from foreign invasion, but she hasn't yet had the heart to calibrate the ancient magic for Lucifer's dark signature. The devil in question cocks his head, sits at the edge of the bed and places a hand at her temple. When he speaks again, his voice is ages older than his youthful appearance would imply. "I need you in Samsara, love." Lilith lifts her head at this, shakes it firmly once, twice. "No, Lucie, absolutely not. I gave you Siren, and Ashes seems determined to keep Cori and the Six in working order. You don't need me there." "I can no longer trust Siren, and Cori's ragamuffins are not my concern. (incomplete)

Nothing's gonna hurt you with my eyes shut, I can see through them I can see through them When Adder smiled, his eyes curved into crescents the color of a swollen blood moon, pale lips drawn back to bare long, hooked fangs. Quinn had heard his cousin's face called beautiful, but all he saw was a dark young man who courted violence and kept company with monsters. The mouth was too long, nose broken too many times, rough skin cracked and split into the bizarre golden seals at his temple. Corinne Adder Nathaniel Reisse never smiled out of kindness. Quinn was exhausted and distraught, working a late shift at the vet clinic just to keep himself busy, an excuse to hide from sleep as long as he could. Adder pushed the door open and the little bells chimed. He smiled, probably intending reassurance. "I heard that he attacked you," the younger demon said, striding forward to lean against the front desk. He scratched the lazy cat sprawled across the counter, eliciting a deep, satisfied purr. Quinn put down his pen, forcing his hands not to tremble. "The god possessing Caolan attacked me, yes." Adder scratched the cat's fluffy belly, still smiling. "They're one and the same, Quinnie. Cao just took a while to remember who he was." "Well. It sounds as though you've figured everything out. Thanks for stopping by." "Are you hurt? He said you might be, even though he tried to control it." Quinn shook his head, rolling the pen back and forth on the counter. "Not a bit hurt. I don't... I don't blame him, whether he really is evil incarnate or not. You can tell him that. If he wants to hear it." "I think he quite liked you, Quinncy." "I liked him too, Nate. He was... he is a good kid. But there's not much I can do for him now." "You could visit him? I'm sure he'd be glad to see you." "Yes, well. I'll just stroll along down to Samsara, also known as the viper pit, and bring him some cookies, shall I?" Adder grinned, giving into Lazycat's demands and cuddling the fat behemoth to his chest. "It's not so bad as all that, really. We've even got a primary school set up, complete with tiny adorable desks." Quinn shrugged, keeping his eyes on the movement of the pen so that he didn't have to look up into his cousin's face. Adder was a charmer, it was how he operated now that he'd abandoned his childhood plan to burn the whole world down. What he couldn't achieve through brute force, he smiled and sweet-talked and suckered his way through. "Well," the soldier said when Quinn had no other words to offer, "if you ever want to see him, I'll be happy to escort you there. You know how to call me." "I do." "Alright. Take care of yourself, Quinnston." "Goodnight, Nate." The door closed and the little bells chimd. Lazycat mrowred forlornly, butting his head against Quinn's arm until the vet sighed and scooped him up. The air was lighter with his cousin gone, the shadows retreating farther into the corners as Quinn rubbed his cheek against Lazycat's thick fur. Of course Adder would be watching out for Caolan now, with the history between him and Ceres. Samsara presented a whole host of negative influences for a boy who'd just lost everything. Samsara. Quinn could go, couldn't he? Sayuri would take him, if he asked. It was hard to be anxious of anything with his sister near. Adder would know better than to smile at Sayuri. And Caolan needed to know that monsters weren't his only friends. Such a promising youth, so quick and clever. Determined to use his power for good. Lazycat made an inquisitive noise, blinking up at his owner. "I don't know," Quinn replied, looking at the door. "I'm thinking."

<lj-cut text="Chiharu">

Name: Chiharael Lunae R'lyeh
Nicknames: Chiharu, Haru
Age: 16
Species: Rabbit
Birthplace: Atzulith
Intelligence Level: High

FAMILY HISTORY

Mother: Atarael
Father: Soviel
Adoptive father: Leviathan
Step-father: Ahriman
Brothers/cousins/step-brother/etc: Virgil, Dante, Remi

PHYSICAL APPEARANCE

Height: 5'8"
Weight: 145
Skin tone: Fair
Eye color: Bright red
Hair color: Black
Sense of style: Doesn't fuss about style, borrows her brothers' clothes and prefers to dress as a boy
Distinguishing marks: Snake-bite piercings, two small hoops that curl over her bottom lip; dermal piercings, six small diamonds set in a bracket below and around the far corner of her left eye; a rabbit-in-the-moon chestpiece tattoo

PSYCHOLOGICAL PROFILE

What does the future have in store?: Joining the Anima Mundi, or the special guard in Hell
Is there anything worth dying for?: Family, righteous social causes
Is there anything she tries to avoid?: Fundamentalist angels, xenophobic demons, romantic comedies
What does she hate?: Prejudice, 'The Notebook', vegetables, formalwear
What does she love?: Her family, science fiction books and movies, dogs, flavored coffees, weapons
What are her strengths?: Clever, physically very strong, a good head for martial arts and strategy; she would go to any lengths to defend a loved one or help someone in need
What are her weaknesses?: Tends to assume the worst of people, wary of strangers and has a hard time opening up to others outside of her family; has a 'shoot first' philosophy
Does she have any hobbies?: Sparring, playing war games, annoying her brothers
Is she a pessimist or optimist?: Bit of a pessimist
Is she a realist or a dreamer?: Realist

BEHAVIORS

What is her way of showing affection?: Very physical, but there are only a few people who receive it
How does she handle grief - does she cry?: Cries at the drop of a hat, but they're usually crocodile tears
How does she tolerate pain?: Very well
Does she have a temper?: Yes, quick to ignite and slow to burn out
Does she make empty promises?: No
Is she blunt?: Yes
What is her sense of humour like?: Knock-knock jokes, puns
How's her energy level?: High, she has to be reminded sometimes to eat and sleep
Does she drink, smoke, or do drugs?: Extremely fond of beer
What is her voice like?: Low, a bit boyish

What do others think of her?: She tries to stay out of the public eye, and even though she has a technical right to the throne, Chiharu removed herself from the line of succession just as her step-brother did. Ordinary citizens of Hell know very little about her, but Ahri asks her to make an appearance at public events like holiday addresses. As a Rabbit, she still faces some bigotry in Heaven - Howl is often unkind to her without meaning to be.</lj-cut>
